      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "a41e0e48-0fd3-475d-a9ac-5c49e44da21c",
      "text": "\"Impact investments can be made in emerging and developed markets, and target a range of returns from below-market to above-market rates, depending upon the circumstances.\" Impact investing tends to have roots in either social issues or environmental issues, and has been contrasted with microfinance. Impact investors actively seek to place capital in businesses, nonprofits, and funds that can harness the positive power of enterprise. Impact investing occurs across asset classes; for example, private equity/venture capital, debt, and fixed income."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "8740370c28557061",
      "text": "# Industry"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "322f080b-97bc-475f-9da0-dc07440b3ea7",
      "text": "The number of funds engaged in impact investing grew quickly over a five-year period and a 2009 report from research firm the [[Monitor Group]] estimated that the impact investing industry could grow from around US$50 billion in assets to US$500 billion in assets within the subsequent decade -\n [http://www.monitorinstitute.com/downloads/what-we-think/impact-investing/Impact_Investing.pdf monitorinstitute.com]"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "15790b8a4e341809",
      "text": "Such capital may be in a range of forms, including equity, debt, working capital lines of credit, and loan guarantees. Examples in recent decades include many investments in microfinance, community development finance, and clean technology."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "56e2250907296dfc",
      "text": "The growth of impact investing is partly attributed to the criticism of traditional forms of philanthropy and [[international development]], which have been characterized as unsustainable and driven by the goals—or whims—of the corresponding donors -\n [http://www.partnersglobal.org/news/impact-investing-for-sustainable-development partnersglobal.org]"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "e09a99b9-31c1-42de-8ed2-84c90f754c05",
      "text": "Currently impact investing is still only a small market when compared to the global equity market, estimated at US$61 trillion (market capitalization of domestic listed companies) by the World Bank in 2015 -\n [https://thegiin.org/impact-investing/need-to-know/ thegiin.org]"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "207aec33993319a3",
      "text": "In contrast, about US$15.2 billion was committed to 7,551 impact investment projects that year, according to GIIN’s 2016 ''Annual Impact Investor Survey''. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "33788359dd5fb918",
      "text": "The largest sectors by asset allocation were housing, microfinance and energy.  For 2016 growth of about 16 percent was expected, reaching approximately US$18 billion -\n [https://www.forbes.com/sites/janetnovack/2017/04/21/why-impact-investing-may-flourish-in-the-age-of-donald-trump/#4ba5cf59a3c6 forbes.com]"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "0be04d5c-75b3-4604-88ba-93df41bd96d0",
      "text": "Many [[development finance institution]]s, such as the British [[Commonwealth Development Corporation]] or Norwegian [[Norfund]], can also be considered impact investors, because they allocate a portion of their portfolio to investments that deliver financial as well as social or environmental benefits -\n [http://www.investopedia.com/articles/investing/060915/impact-investing-how-it-works-and-how-invest.asp investopedia.com]"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "3c6e7737-a036-4dc3-ae40-addda5023662",
      "text": "# Not crowdfunding"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "0def323760e2a328",
      "text": "Impact investing is distinguished from [[crowdfunding]] sites, such as [[Indiegogo]] or [[Kickstarter]], because impact investments are typically debt or equity investments over US$1,000—with longer-than-traditional [[venture capital]] payment times—and an \"exit strategy\". Traditionally this exit strategy would involve an [[Initial public offering]] (IPO) or buyout in the for-profit [[Startup company]]."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "4bbf2c30e3eddd80",
      "text": "Although some social enterprises are nonprofits, impact investing typically involves for-profit, social- or environmental-mission-driven businesses."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "7c80039a-436c-4e9e-a008-cf5b1ca6ec4f",
      "text": "Organizations receiving impact investment capital may be set up legally as a for-profit, not-for profit, [[B Corporation]], Low-profit Limited Liability Company ([[L3C]]), [[Community Interest Company]], or other designations that may vary by country. In much of Europe, these are known as [[social enterprise]]s -\n [http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/1d2b3ed2-aa2e-11e0-94a6-00144feabdc0.html ft.com]"
